A Works Progress Administration art project, done in the Art Deco style. It depicts various aspects of makahiki (harvest festival), imagined as taking place in the vicinity of what is now know as Ala Mona Park, makahiki pa'ani ho'oikaika (annual sports tournaments) are emphasized. This mural shows ali'i (chiefs) guided by the spirit of Lono (one of the four major Hawaiian gods, associated with peace and fertility) being presented with ho'okupu (tribute). In the distance kahuna (priests) guard the kapa (bark cloth) double banner of Lono. In the background are the silhouette of Lae'ahi (Diamond Head) and the village of Waikiki (spouting water). Sports represented are he'e holua (sled racing), mokomoko (hand-to-hand fighting), and 'ulu maika (bowling), dance and music are represented with 'uli'uli (gourd rattle), pahu (drum), and mahiole (helmet).</ds:description>     <ds:location>Lester McCoy Pavilion</ds:location>     <ds:imagefile>http://hiculturearts.pastperfect-online.com/34250images/001/19300101.JPG</ds:imagefile>     <ds:objectid>1930.01.01</ds:objectid>     <ds:discipline>Mural</ds:discipline>     <ds:title>The Makahiki Festival - The Makai Mural</ds:title>     <ds:access>Limited</ds:access>     <ds:latitude>21.290824</ds:latitude>     <ds:longitude>-157.85131</ds:longitude>     <ds:artloc><geo:SpatialThing>         <geo:lat>21.290824</geo:lat>         <geo:long>-157.85131</geo:long></geo:SpatialThing></ds:artloc></dsbase:yef5-h88r> <dsbase:yef5-h88r rdf:about="http://data.honolulu.gov/resource/yef5-h88r/3">     <socrata:rowID>3</socrata:rowID>     <rdfs:member rdf:resource="http://data.honolulu.gov/resource/yef5-h88r"/>     <ds:creator>Sean Browne</ds:creator>     <ds:credit>City and County of Honolulu Purchase</ds:credit>     <ds:date>2001</ds:date>     <ds:description>Bronze figure of Prince Jonah Kuhio Kalanianaole. A Works Progress Administration art project, done in the Art Deco style. It depicts various aspects of makahiki (harvest festival), imagined as taking place in the vicinity of what is now know as Ala Mona Park, makahiki pa'ani ho'oikaika (annual sports tournaments) are emphasized. This mural depicts ali'i with their retainers traveling between villages by wa'a kaulua (double hulled canoe), a carving of Lono and kahili (feather standards) accompany them. Puowaina (Punchbowl) is shown in the background. Also depicted is he'e nalu (surfing) on olo (long surfboard) and 'o'o ihe (sport of spear throwing) whereby a group of men, at a given signal, hurl their spears at one man who would either catch the spears, dodge them, or otherwise fend them off.</ds:description>     <ds:location>Lester McCoy Pavilion</ds:location>     <ds:imagefile>http://hiculturearts.pastperfect-online.com/34250images/001/19300102.JPG</ds:imagefile>     <ds:objectid>1930.01.02</ds:objectid>     <ds:discipline>Mural</ds:discipline>     <ds:title>The Makahiki Festival - The Mauka Mural</ds:title>     <ds:access>Limited</ds:access>     <ds:latitude>21.290959</ds:latitude>     <ds:longitude>-157.851265</ds:longitude>     <ds:artloc><geo:SpatialThing>         <geo:lat>21.290959</geo:lat>         <geo:long>-157.851265</geo:long></geo:SpatialThing></ds:artloc></dsbase:yef5-h88r> <dsbase:yef5-h88r rdf:about="http://data.honolulu.gov/resource/yef5-h88r/5">     <socrata:rowID>5</socrata:rowID>     <rdfs:member rdf:resource="http://data.honolulu.gov/resource/yef5-h88r"/>     <ds:creator>Charles Dickey</ds:creator>     <ds:date>1935</ds:date>     <ds:description>Three sets of double doors and three top panels of an aluminium alloy in the Art Deco style. The bas relief is executed on a series of green steatite stone blocks which depict mythical and human Hawaiian figures, flora, and animals in the upper portions flanking either side of a central doorway as well as stylized letter forming a narrative text beneath the figurative panels. The two panels, one on the Diamond Head side of the entry way and the other on the other side of the entry door both depict stories involving the god Kane and Kaneloa in a mythical story about the discovery and use of water. The body is articulated by using weld material to give the spotty look of the animal. The head is approximately 12" long and it peers down its mouth open, and with long eyelashes. There are ears and horns on its head and there are iron rods of about 4-6" in length that are used to articulate the hairs on the back of the giraffe's neck. The base on which the giraffe sits is made of concrete with stones set into it. The piece was installed at the Honolulu Zoo in 1992.
